patients = read_rds(file.path(dir_data, "patients.rds"))

The primary patient (candidate/recipient) population is: all pediatric HR candidates listed between 2021-01-01 and 2024-06-30

  • pediatric: Under 18 at time of listing
  • HR: using heart (HR) waitlists. Some patients listed for both HR and HL.
  • Waitlist initiated between: 2021-01-01 and 2024-06-30

2.2 DCD Eligible Candidates

Number of Pediatric Candidates open to see offers for DCD heart (WL_DCD_SEQ).

  • No: never open to see DCD offers
  • Yes: always open to see DCD offers
  • No -> Yes: initially listed as not accepting DCD offers, but changed to consider.
  • Yes -> No: initially listed as accepting DCD offers, but changed to no longer consider.
Code 
# Open to DCD offers during time on WL
WL_DCD = 
  waitlists %>% 
  arrange(CHG_DT) %>% 
  distinct(WL_ID_CODE, DONCRIT_ACPT_DCD) %>% 
  mutate(
    DONCRIT_ACPT_DCD = case_match(DONCRIT_ACPT_DCD, "N" ~ "No", "Y" ~ "Yes")
  ) %>% 
  summarize(
    .by = WL_ID_CODE, 
    WL_DCD_SEQ = str_c(DONCRIT_ACPT_DCD, collapse = " -> ")
  )
Code 
WL_DCD %>% 
  count(WL_DCD_SEQ) %>% 
  mutate( p = scales::percent(n/sum(n), 1/10) ) %>% gt()

3 Post-Tx Outcomes

To measure post transplant outcomes, we exclude recipients who donât have a transplant date.

Code 
n_no_txdate = patients %>% filter(TXED == 1) %>% filter(is.na(TX_DATE))  %>% nrow()

This excludes \(n = 6\) recipients.

Removing data for patients that were adult (AGE_AT_TX >= 18) at time of transplant.

Code 
n_turned_18 = patients %>%  filter(AGE_AT_TX >= 18) %>% nrow()

This excludes \(n = 45\) recipients.

Code 
post_tx = 
  patients %>% 
  filter(AGE_AT_TX < 18) %>% 
  filter(TXED == 1) %>%        # only transplants
  filter(!is.na(TX_DATE)) %>%  # not missing transplant date
  mutate(
    EV_TIME = coalesce(EV_TIME, 0), # set EV_TIME = 0 if missing
    EV_TYPE = coalesce(EV_TYPE, 0)  # set EV_TYPE = 0 if missing
  ) %>% 
  left_join(WL_DCD, by = "WL_ID_CODE")

This leaves \(n = 1540\) recipients in our post-tx data.

3.4 Survival Plot (Individual)

Hereâs an alternative visualization showing the individual transplants. There is a horizontal grey line for each transplant. If the line ends in a solid black dot, then the recipient died or had graft failure at that time. If the line ends in an open blue circle, then recipient is censored at that time. The tick marks at the bottom and right side correspond to death/failure events. The diagonal orange line shows the observation window.

Code 
days_observed = 
  tibble(
    TX_DATE = seq(as.Date("2021-01-01"), as.Date("2024-07-01"), by = "1 day"),
    days = difftime(as.Date("2024-07-01"), TX_DATE, units = "days") %>% 
      as.numeric()
  )

event_labels = c("Alive/Censored", "Death or Graft Failure")

post_tx %>% 
  transmute(
    AGE_AT_TX,
    STATUS_AT_TX,
    TX_YEAR,
    TX_DATE,
    DCD_DON = case_match(DCD_DON, "N" ~ 'DBD', "Y" ~ "DCD"),
    WL_DCD_SEQ,
    EV_TIME, 
    EV_TYPE = factor(EV_TYPE), # = case_match(EV_TYPE, 1 ~ "Death or Graft Failure", 0 ~ "Censored"),
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = 0, xend = EV_TIME, y = TX_DATE, yend = TX_DATE)) + 
  facet_wrap(~DCD_DON) + 
  geom_line(data = days_observed, aes(x = days, y = TX_DATE), color = "orange", alpha = .75, inherit.aes = FALSE) + 
  geom_segment(alpha = .25, color = "grey60") + 
  # plot censored events first so events show more clearly
  geom_point(data = . %>% filter(EV_TYPE == 0), 
             aes(x = EV_TIME, color = EV_TYPE, shape = EV_TYPE), 
             size = .8) + 
  geom_point(data = . %>% filter(EV_TYPE == 1), 
             aes(x = EV_TIME, color = EV_TYPE, shape = EV_TYPE), 
             size = .8) + 
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(1, 19), labels = event_labels) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#A3C2DF", "black"), labels = event_labels) + 
  geom_rug(data = . %>% filter(EV_TYPE == 1), aes(x = EV_TIME), alpha = .50, length = unit(.02, "npc")) + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1500, by = 180)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(
    trans = c("date", "reverse")
  ) + 
  labs(
    x = "Days since transplant",
    y = "Transplant date", 
    color = "Event Type",
    shape = "Event Type"
  ) + 
   theme(
     legend.position = "inside",
     legend.position.inside = c(.88, 1-.90), 
     legend.key.size = unit(0.3, "cm"),
     legend.background = element_rect(color = "black", fill = "transparent"),
     legend.title = element_text(size = 10)
   )

3.5 Other post-tx comparison ideas

I did try to implement a causal survival forest to estimate the change in survival probability (or mean survival time) due to DCD donor. However, there isnât enough DCD data to avoid the copious warnings that results are unstable. FYI - there was no detected change in survival using DCD, but again, this isnât very meaningful due to the limited sample size.

Another idea is to fit a cox survival model to the DBD recipients (using all covariates) and predict the survival time for the DCD recipients. We can evaluate if DCD survival is longer/shorter than expected.

3.6 DCD Recipients vs.Â DCD Candidates

There are some DCD candidates that ended up getting DBD hearts. This is an interesting group because if there are differences in a patients that prompts their listing centers to accept DCD, this can account for it. In other words compare outcomes for DCD candidates that received DBD vs.Â received DCD hearts.

stat_test <- function(data, var, group = DCD_DON){
  x = data %>% pull({{group}})
  y = data %>% pull({{var}})
  var_name = data %>% select(any_of({{var}})) %>% colnames()
  
  # MannâWhitney U / WilcoxonâMannâWhitney test
  if(is.numeric(y)) 
    test = wilcox.test(y~x)
  # Fisher's Exact Test
  else if(nlevels(factor(y)) < 10) test = fisher.test(table(x,y))
  else test = fisher.test(table(x,y), simulate.p.value = 1000)

  out = tibble(var = var_name, p_value = test$p.value, test = test$method)
  return(out)
}

details_cat <- function(data, var, group = DCD_DON){
  data %>% 
    count({{group}}, {{var}}) %>% 
    mutate(.by = {{group}}, p = n / sum(n)) %>% 
    mutate(
      stat = glue::glue("{n} ({round(p, 3) %>% str_pad(width = 5, side = 'right', pad = 0)})")
    ) %>% 
    select(-n, -p) %>% 
    spread({{group}}, stat) %>% 
    gt()  
}

details_num <- function(data, var, group = DCD_DON){
  data %>% 
  summarize(
    .by = {{group}},
    n = sum(!is.na({{var}})),
    Q1 = quantile({{var}}, probs = .25, na.rm=TRUE),
    median = median({{var}}, na.rm=TRUE),
    Q3 = quantile({{var}}, probs = .75, na.rm=TRUE),
    IQR = glue::glue("({round(Q1)}, {round(Q3)})"),
    stat = glue::glue("{round(median)} ({round(Q1)}, {round(Q3)})")
  ) %>% 
  select(
    DONOR_TYPE = {{group}}, n, median, IQR, stat
  ) %>% 
  gt() %>% 
  tab_header(title = enquo(var)) # warning message. use as_label() or as_name()
}

4 Waitlist Outcomes

There are many challenges in trying to understand changes in waitlist time. The main difficulty is that this is a competing risks problem, not survival, because there are many reasons to be removed from the waitlist (e.g., dead, improvement, removed in error, listed at two centers). One of the other studies compared median waitimes for transplanted patients; this is misleading because sicker patients may not make it to transplant and arenât included in the analysis. This issue makes it difficult to estimate median time to transplant.

The other issues are that candidates change status, change DCD acceptability, and refuse (good) offers. Plus the usual issues impacting wait time: size, ABO, Listing Center (or geographic location which impacts number of donors within distance bands).

Iâm still trying to work out a good method to assess waiting times. In the mean time here are some other metrics related to waitlist outcomes.

4.1 Outcome Rates

This looks at the waitlist outcomes for each type of DCD Listed Candidate.

Waitlist outcomes:

  • Success: âDeceased Donor tx, removed by tx centerâ, âCand. condition improved, tx not neededâ, âTx at another center (multiple-listing)â.

  • Adverse: âDiedâ, âCand. cond. deteriorated,too sick to txâ

  • Other: all other reasons for waitlist removal like âTransferred to another centerâ, âRefused transplantâ, âUnable to contact candidateâ, âCandidate Removed in Errorâ

  • Still on waitlist: candidate is still on waitlist at time of data collection

4.2 âGood Offersâ

A âgoodâ offer is one from a donor that was eventually accepted by some candidate and the refusal code isnât related to size mismatch. We can adjust this definition as necessary. See below for some basic statistics.

Code

good_offers = 
  offers %>% 
  mutate(
    DCD_DON = coalesce(DCD_DON, "N"), # replace unknown DCD with No

4.3 Offer Rates and Time between offers

This section looks at the offer rates and time between offers. Note that we are not actually using the exact offer time, but time of the match run for the offer. Since centers have 30 mins to respond, the actual time of the offer is longer, especially for candidates far down on the match run list.
We donât have the exact offer time; we have the response time, but it is very noisy with many outliers.

#: Calculate time between two date-times (year, month, day, hour, minute, second)
#  Note: this function ignores timezones so be sure DT1 and DT2 have same tz. 
library(lubridate)
calc_dur <- function(DT1, DT2, units = "days"){
  if(tz(DT1) != tz(DT2)) warning("DT1 does not have same timezone as DT2")
  int = lubridate::interval(DT1, DT2)
  lubridate::time_length(int, unit = units)
}
Code 
tmp2 =

  arrange(WL_ID_CODE, CHG_DT) %>% # data must be ordered

    .by = WL_ID_CODE,

    dt_STATUS = lag(STATUS),        # status for calculation
    dt_ACCEPT_DCD = lag(ACCEPT_DCD) # dcd accept flag for calculation

    n_good_dcd_offers = sum(type == "OFFER" & DCD_DON == "Y" & GOOD_OFFER),

4.3.3 Modeling Rates

The previous analysis didnât consider factors that impact time on waitlist such as blood type, size, and listing center (i.e., geographic location and donor availability).

Code 
model_data = 
  tmp2 %>% 
  mutate(wt = wt_raw) %>% 
  left_join(
    read_rds(file.path(dir_data, "data_candidate.rds")) %>% 
    select(
      WL_ID_CODE, 
      WEIGHT_CAND_KG, #BSA_CAND, PHM_CAND
      ABO_CAND,
      # Note: AGE < 2 allows non-blood type match
    ), 
    by = "WL_ID_CODE"
  ) %>% 
  left_join(
    patients %>% select(WL_ID_CODE, AGE_AT_LISTING, LISTING_CTR_CODE),
    by = "WL_ID_CODE"
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    ABO_CAND = factor(ABO_CAND, c( "A", "B", "AB", "O")),
    # AGE_UNDER_1 = At time of offer
    LISTING_CTR_CODE = factor(LISTING_CTR_CODE)
  )

We are modeling the log offer rate = Intercept + ACCEPT_DCD + STATUS + ABO + WEIGHT + LISTING_CTR_CODE. The intercept corresponds to candidate with Status 1A and ABO: A.

The coefficient of interest in the ACCEPT_DCD with indicates if a candidate is open to DCD offers. \(\exp(\text{ACCEPT\_DCD})\) corresponds to the increase in offer rate.

Note: Candidate weight and listing center wonât show up in the coefficient table because they are modeled with smoothing splines and as random effects, respectively. We can get more details and show the effect of weight and listing center as need arises.

Code 
library(mgcv)
fit_gam <- function(outcome_var = "n_offers", data = model_data, family = poisson()){
  
  fmla =  formula(str_c(outcome_var, 
                        ' ~ ACCEPT_DCD + STATUS + ABO_CAND + s(WEIGHT_CAND_KG) + s(LISTING_CTR_CODE, bs = "re")'))
  fit = 
  mgcv::gam(
    fmla,
    offset = log(days),
    weights = wt,
    family = family,
    data = data)   
  return(fit)
}

Code 
format_pvalue <- function(p){
  case_when(
    p >= 0.01 ~ scales::number(p, accuracy = 1/10^3),
    .default = "< 0.01"
  )
}

make_table_row <- function(data, var, group = WL_DCD_SEQ_2, decimals = 2){
  x = data %>% pull({{group}})
  y = data %>% pull({{var}})
  var_name = data %>% select(any_of({{var}})) %>% colnames()  
  # group_name = data %>% select({{group}}) %>% colnames()  
  
  # MannâWhitney U / WilcoxonâMannâWhitney test
  if(is.numeric(y) && n_distinct(y) > 2){ 
    test = wilcox.test(y~x)
    tab = 
      tibble(x,y) %>% 
      summarize(
        .by = x,
        median = median(y, na.rm=TRUE) %>% scales::number(accuracy = 10^(-decimals)),
        Q1 = quantile(y, .25, na.rm=TRUE) %>% scales::number(accuracy = 10^(-decimals)),
        Q3 = quantile(y, .75, na.rm=TRUE) %>% scales::number(accuracy = 10^(-decimals)),
        cell = glue::glue("{median} ({Q1}, {Q3})")
      )
    out = 
      tab %>% 
      select(x, cell) %>% 
      pivot_wider(names_from = x, values_from = cell) %>% 
      mutate(variable = var_name, x = "", .before = 1) %>% 
      mutate(p_value = format_pvalue(test$p.value), test = test$method)
    
  } else if(all(y %in% c(0,1))){
    # Binary proportion (Use Fisher's Exact Test)
    tab = 
      tibble(x,y) %>% 
      summarize(.by = x, y = sum(y), n = n()) %>% 
      mutate(
        cell = glue::glue("{y} ({scales::percent(y/n, accuracy = 1)})")
      )
    #test = prop.test(x = tab$y, n = tab$n)  
    test = fisher.test(table(x,y))
    out = 
      tab %>% 
      select(x, cell) %>% 
      pivot_wider(names_from = x, values_from = cell) %>% 
      mutate(variable = var_name, x = "",  .before = 1) %>% 
      mutate(p_value = format_pvalue(test$p.value), test = test$method)
    
  } else {
    # Fisher's Exact Test
    if(nlevels(factor(y)) < 10) test = fisher.test(table(x,y))
    else test = fisher.test(table(x,y), simulate.p.value = 1000)  
    
    tab = 
      tibble(x,y) %>% 
      count(x,y) %>% 
      complete(x,y, fill = list(n = 0)) %>% 
      mutate(
        .by = x,
        p = (n / sum(n)) %>% scales::percent(accuracy = 1),
        cell = glue::glue("{n} ({p})")
      )
    out = 
      tab %>% 
      select(x, y, cell) %>% 
      pivot_wider(names_from = x, values_from = cell) %>% 
      rename(x = 1) %>% 
      mutate(variable = ifelse(row_number() == 1, var_name, ""), .before = 1) %>% 
      mutate(
        p_value = ifelse(row_number() == 1, format_pvalue(test$p.value), ""),
        test = ifelse(row_number() == 1, test$method, "")
      )

    
  }
  
  return(out %>% select(-test))
}
